ce:section.ce:para:
The scattering and interference of high-frequency electron sources can cause different degrees of damage to people and electronic equipment [1,2]. The development of new technology and changes in lifestyle cannot prevent us from the effects of electromagnetic radiation. Therefore, the development of a new type of microwave absorbing material can help reduce the harm caused by electromagnetic. Generally, the theoretical difficulties faced by microwave absorbing materials are mainly concentrated in two aspects: i) according to the classical electromagnetic theory, due to the existence of attenuation constant (α), conductive material will produce a strong skin effect in a high-frequency electromagnetic field, which prevents microwave from entering the material and also produces strong reflections [3–5]; ii) according to the light absorption theory of solids, the intrinsic absorption of materials requires electrons in the valence band to absorb photons to transition to the conduction band to form electron-hole pairs, and the absorption process must satisfy the Planck-Einstein equation (
E = h υ
). Therefore, exploring novel lightweight microwave absorption materials with low reflection and wide frequency range is still a noble mission [6].

According to classical electromagnetic theory, the consumption of electromagnetic wave energy by materials is mainly divided into electrical loss and magnetic loss. For traditional microwave absorbing materials, there are usually two parts: the electrical loss part with conductor material as the main body; the magnetic loss part with magnetic material as the ligand. The heterostructure formed by the two materials usually has better microwave absorption performance. However, this type of material has some problems that have to be faced. If the proportion of conductors in the material is too large, it will cause a strong polarization phenomenon, which will produce a skin effect, cause strong reflection, and prevent electromagnetic waves from entering the material. If the magnetic loss of the material is too large, it will increase the weight of the material and affect the conductivity of the conductor. Due to the existence of α, the high-frequency electromagnetic wave is polarized and magnetized after contacting the conductor. The conductive current and induced magnetic field are generated on the surface of the conductor to absorb the energy of the external electromagnetic field. This part of the absorbed energy must satisfy the Planck-Einstein formula (
E = h υ
). Therefore, the GQDs covered by the F-BNNs surface play a very important role in microwave absorption performance.
